                            HOW TO CHEATPROOF QUESTS
     _________________________________________________________________
   
   
   
USE LOGS
Log the time and date when a player first enters your quest area and the
time and date the player solves the quest.  This will tell you if a player
solves the quest unusually fast.  It will also tell you the average amount
of time it takes a player to solve the quest.

DEST QUEST ITEMS
Make quest items dest on sell.  Clean the players inventory of quest items
upon completion.  If your area is a closed quest zone, have the quest items
dest upon leaving the area. If the quest isn't a party quest, dest items on
give.
  
MAKE THE WARNINGS CLEAR
This statement is in quest design, because it is fair to players to do so. 
It is here because players will cheat without meaning to, in an attempt to
keep their friends from dying to an "unfair" death.  If you don't want one
player warning another about a death trap in your questzone.  Give the
warning in the quest area.

   
THE PLAYER SHOULD BE ABLE TO FINISH WITHOUT KNOWLEDGE OF FUTURE EVENTS
Another repeat.  Don't make players want to warn their friends about some
minor thing they have to do at the beginning in order to avoid something
going wrong later.   

 
MAKE FORGIVING SYNTAX
I hate syntax!  Having to come up with some obscure syntax that isn't an
intuitive reaction in the room:
The brick looks loose --- syntax: loosen brick  Now why would I do that it
is already loose?  Don't use obscure syntax to make a quest more difficult.

INDIVIDUALIZE THINGS
Making items id to the player who found them makes it much more difficult
fore players to go get them for others and give them away.  There is a good
example of an individualized quest item /open/OBJ/genqob.c

MAKE QUESTS RANDOM
Making the items load randomly in different locations depending on the
player makes it more difficult for players to share quest info. Look
in /open/QUEST/random for an example of how to do this.

MAKE MULTIPLE SOLUTIONS
If the quest is to end the war between the elves and vikings in hyper, give
the players a choice.  Let them choose who wins.  Have more than one quest
running through the same area, but only one first hint.  Set the first hint to
randomly send the player on one of a number of quests and have the solution 
dependant on which hint the player got.  Cheaters will get information from 
more than one source and are likely to follow the wrong leads (and therefore 
give themselves away).

CHANGE YOUR QUEST WITHOUT WARNING
Here's where those logs come in handy.  If you know a player is working on the
quest, don't change it.  But if no one has entered the area recently then
change the quest slightly without notifying players.


